Requirements ROSAMOND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT NO. 1 This ROSAMOND SHARED FACILITIES AGREEMENT NO. 1 (the Agreement ), dated as of February 17, 2016 (the Execution Date ), is entered into by and among SOLAR STAR CALIFORNIA XLI, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 1 Project Company ), GOLDEN FIELDS SOLAR I, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 2 Project Company ), GOLDEN FIELDS SOLAR II, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 3 Project Company ), GOLDEN FIELDS SOLAR III, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 4 Project Company ), GOLDEN FIELDS SOLAR IV, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ( Phase 5 Project Company ), other co-tenants party hereto from time to time (collectively with Phase 1 Project Company, Phase 2 Project Company, Phase 3 Project Company, Phase 4 Project Company and Phase 5 Project Company, the Co-Tenants and each separately, a Co-Tenant ), and SUNPOWER CAPITAL SERVICES, LLC, a Delaware limited liability company, in the capacity of the Manager hereunder. The Co-Tenants and Manager may be referred to collectively herein, as the Parties, and each separately as a Party . RECITALS: A. The Co-Tenants are each separately developing and will each separately construct, own and operate electricity generation, storage and/or transmission projects, including solar energy generation projects, on real property in Kern County, California. B. Phase 1 Project Company s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 1 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-1 attached hereto. C. Phase 2 Project Company s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 2 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-2 attached hereto. D. Phase 3 Project Company s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 3 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-3 attached hereto. E. Phase 4 Project Company s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 4 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-4 attached hereto. F. Phase 5 Project Company s energy project includes photovoltaic electrical generating arrays and related infrastructure (the Phase 5 Project ) to be located approximately on the real property described on Exhibit A-5 attached hereto. G. The Co-Tenants may from time to time, themselves or through affiliated project companies, or may permit their Third-Party Project Users (as defined below) to, develop additional energy generation, storage or transmission projects of any technology or type, other than a solar energy generation project, developed as a separate electrical transmission route for the delivery of electricity generated by a Project or as CAISO behind the meter generation projects intended to provide electrical energy to the CAISO electrical grid when the output of the Projects is not utilizing the entire interconnection capacity of the Interconnection Agreements, which other projects may be located on their Project Sites or on additional real property now held or hereafter acquired by a Co-Tenant or its affiliated project companies (each, a Secondary Project , and collectively, the Secondary Projects ). H. From time to time herein, the Co-Tenants respective project sites described above may be each individually referred to as a Project Site, and collectively referred to as the Project Sites, and the Co-Tenants respective projects described above (including the Secondary Projects) are each individually referred to as a Project , and collectively as the Projects . I. Each Co-Tenant holds or shall hold its own individual real property rights (by fee ownership, lease, easement, right of way, or otherwise) to its respective Project Site. J. Phase 1 Project Company, Phase 2 Project Company, Phase 3 Project Company, Phase 4 Project Company and Phase 5 Project Company are pursuing the joint Q506 Interconnection Agreement for interconnection services with CAISO and SCE. Alternatively, Phase 4 Project Company and/or Phase 5 Project Company may elect to enter into a separate Interconnection Agreement for interconnection services with an Interconnection Provider. K. The Co-Tenants are also tenants in common with respect to, or are acquiring as tenants in common, certain lease, easement, license and permit rights, all of which are more particularly described on Exhibit B-1 attached hereto (the Shared Premises Agreements ), to use, or will otherwise own fee or easement interests in, certain real property more particularly described on Exhibit B-2 attached hereto (as amended and supplemented from time to time, the Shared Premises ). The Co-Tenants will require the use and possession of specified portions of the Shared Premises for the construction, operation, and maintenance of their respective Projects. L. The Co-Tenants use of the Shared Premises shall also include the construction, operation, and maintenance of certain common infrastructure facilities supporting the construction, operation and maintenance of their respective Projects, including a substation, certain electrical transmission and communication facilities, operation and maintenance facilities, access roads, and lay-down and staging areas for construction, all more particularly described below as the Shared Facilities. M. The Co-Tenants wish to set forth herein their respective rights and obligations regarding the joint design, procurement, development, construction, installation, ownership, use, maintenance, repair, replacement of, and additions to the Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises. I. The Co-Tenants also wish to contract with Manager for the provision of certain limited services to be performed at the pleasure of the Co-Tenants with respect to the Interconnection Agreements, Shared Facilities and the Shared Premises, and the Manager wishes to accept said engagement, on the terms and conditions contained herein. This Agreement shall commence on the earlier of the Execution Date and any later date this Agreement is made effective by FERC ( Effective Date ) and remain in full force and effect following the Effective Date until the first occurrence of one of the following: (a) a single Co-Tenant becomes the owner of the entire ownership interest in all of the Shared Assets, (b) the mutual agreement of all the Co-Tenants, or (c) otherwise as may be provided under this Agreement. 3. SHARED ASSETS 3.1 Shared Facilities. The Co-Tenants shall procure, install, and/or construct, as applicable, the Shared Facilities on the Shared Premises, as more particularly described on Exhibit C attached hereto. 3.2 Partial Conveyance of Co-tenancy Interests in Shared Facilities. In consideration of the mutual covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, effective upon the completion or installation of each component of the Shared Facilities on the Shared Premises, upon and subject to the terms, conditions, restrictions and reservations set forth in this Agreement and in the applicable Shared Premises Agreements, including the receipt of any required prior FERC authorization for conveyances that occur after the Shared Facilities are energized, if applicable, the Constructing Co-Tenant(s) shall be deemed to have GRANTED, SOLD, TRANSFERRED, ASSIGNED, and CONVEYED, and do hereby GRANT, SELL, TRANSFER, ASSIGN, AND CONVEY unto each of the other Co-Tenants an undivided ownership interest in and to such component of Shared Facilities constructed or installed by the Constructing Co-Tenant(s), in each case in proportion to the Segment Interest of the respective transferee Co-Tenant, AS IS, WITH ALL FAULTS AND WITHOUT ANY REPRESENTATIONS OR WARRANTIES WHATSOEVER, EITHER EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, AND SPECIFICALLY EXCLUDING ANY WARRANTY OF TITLE, MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, OR ANY OTHER WARRANTY ARISING UNDER STATUTORY OR COMMON LAW, while at the same time reserving to itself an undivided ownership interest in and to such component of Shared Facilities in the amount of its Segment Interest. The intent of the foregoing is that each Co-Tenant shall acquire and hold an undivided tenancy in common interest in each of the Shared Facilities in proportion to its respective Segment Interest so as to provide for the joint ownership of the Shared Facilities (along with all appurtenant rights) by the Co-Tenants subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement. The foregoing undivided tenancy in common interest of each Co-Tenant in the Shared Facilities may be referred to from time to time in this Agreement as an Undivided Interest . 3.3 Shared Interconnection Agreement. The Q506 Interconnection Agreement shall be shared by the Q506 Co-Tenants as allowed for therein. The Co-Tenants acknowledge that the Q506 Co-Tenants are bound to the co-tenancy elements set forth in Exhibit I hereto. Provided that the terms of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and this Agreement are met, any Co-Tenant may enter into other Interconnection Agreements to facilitate the delivery of power from such Co-Tenant s Project. 3.4 Shared Premises Agreements and Land Matters . A Co-Tenant s exercise of rights with respect to each portion of its Undivided Interest shall be subject to the Co-Tenant having rights to use the Shared Premises on which the applicable Shared Facilities are located under the applicable Shared Premises Agreements or otherwise. Each Co-Tenant shall comply with all the terms and conditions of the Shared Premises Agreements, the Land Matters, and the Governmental Approvals. Any amounts due under the terms of the Shared Premises Agreements shall be paid by the Manager, subject to reimbursement by the Co-Tenants in accordance with Section 4 below. No Shared Premises Agreement may be terminated, modified or amended without the consent of all of the Co-Tenants that are party to, or that directly enjoy rights or benefits under, such Shared Premises Agreement, unless such amendment or modification relates only to the interest of the amending Co-Tenants and does not increase the liabilities or obligations or diminish the right, title or interest of the other Co-Tenants thereunder. Nevertheless, if any Co-Tenant wishes to terminate its interest in a Shared Premises Agreement, and such termination (i) is permitted by the Shared Premises Agreement itself or by the counterparty thereto and (ii) will have no adverse effect on the other Co-Tenants thereto, then the Co-Tenant may terminate its interest in that Shared Premises Agreement. The permitted termination by a Co-Tenant of its interest in a Shared Premises Agreement shall not cause or be deemed to cause the release of the Co-Tenant for any liabilities or obligations accruing under or with respect to such Shared Premises Agreement prior to such termination. 3.5 Access to Shared Facilities. Subject to Section 3.3 above, each Co-Tenant and its Representatives shall have access to the Shared Facilities (a) for inspection of the Shared Facilities, (b) for any required maintenance or repairs of the Shared Facilities agreed to be undertaken by the Co-Tenants or not performed by the Manager in accordance with Section 8 of this Agreement, and (c) for the operation of the Shared Facilities, all in accordance with this Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, except in the event of an Emergency, each Co-Tenant shall provide no less than twenty-four (24) hours prior notice to Manager and the other Co-Tenants of its intent to access the Shared Facilities, and no less than forty-eight (48) hours prior notice to Manager and the other Co-Tenants prior to performing any maintenance or repairs pursuant to clause (b) above. A Co-Tenant and/or any Co-Tenant s Representatives shall follow all applicable safety, security and site rules established by the agreement of the Co-Tenants and Manager, and shall comply with the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and all applicable Shared Premises Agreements, Land Matters, applicable Law and Governmental Approvals when on the Shared Premises or accessing the Shared Facilities, except to the extent that following any such rule would violate applicable Law. In the event of an Emergency, prior notice is not required to access the Shared Facilities to respond to the Emergency, but the Co-Tenant shall provide notice of access to Manager and the other Co-Tenants as soon as reasonably practicable thereafter (no more than twenty four (24) hours after access). 3.6 No Interference, Cooperation and Over-Burdening. 3.6.1 A Co-Tenant s use of the Shared Assets or the operation of its Project (including addition of any storage capacity (through the development and operation of a Secondary Project or otherwise) or other Project Specific Assets) may not interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Co-Tenants of their respective rights in such Shared Assets or the operation or interconnection of their Projects, except as specifically provided herein. Subject to the terms and conditions of this Agreement, including Section 6.17 below, each of the Co-Tenants hereby consents to the development and operation of the Projects, and each of the Co-Tenants shall cooperate in good faith to accommodate each of the other Co-Tenant s uses of the Shared Assets for the benefit of each other s Projects as contemplated by this Agreement. 3.6.2 Each Co-Tenant acknowledges and agrees that the use of the Shared Assets by the Projects as contemplated herein does not, separately or in the aggregate, constitute an overburdening of the Shared Assets, or any part thereof. 3.6.3 No Co-Tenant will use or permit the use of the Shared Assets in any manner that would create waste or nuisance, or that would jeopardize the issuance or maintenance of any insurance policy relating to the Shared Assets or any Governmental Approval as to the Shared Assets or any Project, nor otherwise conduct or cause to be conducted operations on its Project Site or on the Shared Premises which would have similar effects on, or otherwise damage or interfere with, the Shared Assets. 3.6.4 None of the Q506 Co-Tenants may cause or permit the Q506 Interconnection Agreement to be amended without prior written consent of the other Q506 Co-Tenants and written notice thereof to all other Co-Tenants who are not Q506 Co-Tenants. Notwithstanding the foregoing or any other provision in this Agreement to the contrary, Phase 3 Project Company, Phase 4 Project Company and/or Phase 5 Project Company may submit a modification request under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement to reduce their respective interconnection capacity rights thereunder without consent of the other Q506 Co-Tenants after providing prior written notice thereof to the other Q506 Co-Tenants together with a copy of the proposed modification request; provided that such reduction shall not (x) have an adverse impact on any of the other Q506 Co-Tenants rights or obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, including interconnection service rights, rights to receive refunds of Network Upgrade costs from the Participating TO thereunder, or the cost sharing provisions hereunder with respect to payment obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement for the costs for installing and constructing the interconnection facilities of the Interconnection Customer , including the Shared Facilities hereunder, for the Participating TO s construction costs for which the Interconnection Customer is responsible under and as defined in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement or (y) result in a material increase in operating costs for a Q506 Co-Tenant that has outstanding obligations under a project finance debt facility secured solely by the assets of, or direct or indirect equity interest in, its Project. For the avoidance of doubt, any Liabilities incurred by the other Q506 Co-Tenants as a result of any such modification request would be covered by the indemnity provisions of Section 11. 3.6.5 Without limiting Co-Tenants obligations under Sections 3.8, 6.1 or 6.17, in the event of any conflict of use rights in Electrical Facilities between any Co-Tenants Projects (including any Secondary Project Co-Tenant s Secondary Project) resulting from an Emergency or an unplanned outage or a reduction of capacity of the Electrical Facilities, the Manager shall allocate the remaining capacity of the Electrical Facilities in a non-discriminatory manner among the Projects in accordance with their Percentage Interests. 3.6.6 No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Project to the Shared Facilities to the extent such interconnection will result in (a) such Co-Tenant having a Project with a nameplate capacity in excess of its applicable maximum capacity set forth in Section 1 of Appendix C to the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, if such Co-Tenant is party thereto or (b) such Co-Tenant having a Project with a nameplate capacity in excess of the difference between 409 MW and the aggregate nameplate capacity for all other Projects. To the extent that conditions exist which result in an Co-Tenant generating energy from its respective Project in excess of its Percentage Interest of the aggregate capacity for all Projects set forth in Exhibit D, then such Co-Tenant shall curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Percentage Interest of such aggregate capacity. 3.7 Additional Real Property Rights and Facilities 3.7.1 To the extent that any additional real property and rights therein ( Additional Shared Premises ) or physical facilities ( Additional Shared Facilities, together with the Additional Shared Premises, the Additional Shared Assets ) that relate to the Shared Assets or operation thereof, are required by any Co-Tenant to continue operating its Project, to modify its Project or to repower its Project, the Co-Tenant or the Manager may give written notice to the other Co-Tenants of such requirement, with a reasonable explanation of why such Additional Shared Assets are needed. Each Co-Tenant receiving such notice shall have thirty (30) days after receiving such notice to determine if such Additional Shared Assets are also needed for its Project and to so notify all the other Co-Tenants and Manager in writing of its election to participate in the acquisition, installation, and/or construction of such Additional Shared Assets. A Co-Tenant s failure to notify the other Co-Tenants and Manager of its election to participate within such thirty (30) days period will be deemed an election to decline the addition of the proposed Additional Shared Assets to the Shared Assets. Any Additional Shared Assets that a Majority of the Co-Tenants agree to add to the Shared Assets to be governed by this Agreement shall be (a) procured jointly by the Co-Tenants which elect to use the Additional Shared Assets, (b) added to the Shared Premises and/or Shared Facilities, as applicable, under this Agreement (as a new Segment in the case of new Shared Facilities), and (c) held in undivided ownership interests by the acquiring Co-Tenants, in proportion with each such Co-Tenants relative Percentage Interest (or as the acquiring Co-Tenants may otherwise agree among themselves in the case of a new Segment of Shared Facilities) to be governed by the terms of this Agreement. If a Majority of the Co-Tenants do not agree to add Additional Shared Assets requested by a Co-Tenant or the Manager under this Section, then nothing herein shall prevent the requesting Co-Tenant (or any group of them) from acquiring the additional premises or facilities needed by and to be held by such Co-Tenant(s), not as part of the Shared Assets hereunder, and not subject to the terms of this Agreement, provided that any additional facilities so acquired shall not, in the reasonable judgment of the Co-Tenants, interfere with the development, construction, operation, usage, interconnection or the maintenance of the Shared Assets, the other Co-Tenants Projects (including Secondary Projects), or otherwise violate the terms and conditions of this Agreement, the Land Matters, Governmental Approvals or applicable Laws. 3.7.2 To the extent that any Co-Tenant or its Third-Party Project User desires any Additional Shared Assets to develop and construct any Secondary Projects, such Co-Tenant may, or may permit the applicable Third-Party Project User to, elect to procure and/or construct such Additional Shared Assets in its sole discretion, subject to the conditions of Section 3.8 below. 3.7.3 Except as otherwise provided in this Agreement or as expressly permitted by the terms of the applicable Shared Premises Agreements, no Co-Tenant shall construct, install or place any additional facilities within the Shared Premises without the consent of other Co-Tenants, not to be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary, nothing in this Section 3.7.3 shall preclude a Co-Tenant from constructing, installing or placing any of such Co-Tenant s Project Specific Assets on any portion of the Shared Premises that is also leased by such Co-Tenant, subject to the compliance with the provisions of Section 3.6 of this Agreement. 3.8 Conditions to Installation of Additional Shared Facilities or Connecting Projects to the Shared Facilities. Any Co-Tenant installing Additional Shared Facilities or connecting its Project (including any Secondary Project) to the Shared Facilities shall (a) not interfere with the use or access by the other Co-Tenants of the Shared Facilities, except as may be necessary during the installation, repair, or replacement of Shared Facilities, (b) to the extent commercially reasonable, schedule during an off-peak and/or down-time period any required disconnection of the Shared Facilities to conduct construction activities to minimize the impact on the Projects of the other Co-Tenants, (c) provide to each of the Co-Tenants and the Manager at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of commencement of such construction activities together with a reasonably detailed description thereof, (d) provide at least thirty (30) days prior written notice of any planned outages, and the durations thereof, of the Shared Facilities that would result in a disconnection of another Co-Tenant s Project, (e) take into consideration, to the extent commercially reasonable, any changes in the construction plans or timing of construction required by another Co-Tenant, provided that the other Co-Tenant does not attempt to interfere with the installation of the proposed Additional Shared Facilities, unless such installation can reasonably be expected to result in an Emergency or violate the terms of the Shared Premises Agreements, any Interconnection Agreement, the Land Matters, Governmental Approvals, applicable Laws, or this Agreement, (f) be responsible for obtaining and complying with any necessary Governmental Approvals and providing documentary evidence of such Governmental Approvals to the Co-Tenants and Manager, and (g) compensate the other Co-Tenants Projects for lost revenues as a result of lost generation due to an outage or disconnection of such Co-Tenants Projects. Any Co-Tenants installing Additional Shared Facilities or other facilities that are needed by or would benefit less than all of the Co-Tenants, or connecting its own Project to the Shared Facilities, shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenants from all Liabilities, including third party claims, property and revenue losses incurred, as a result of such construction or installation activities, to the extent such claims and damages are not covered by the insurance required by Section 12. Installation of Additional Shared Facilities to be owned by more than one Co-Tenant shall be installed jointly by the participating Co-Tenants or by the Manager at the direction of the participating Co-Tenants and will be at the risk of all the participating Co-Tenants, and each participating Co-Tenant shall have the right to review and approve all design, planning and installation elements in connection with such installation, and will bear any risk of loss thereof in proportion with its Segment Interest in the Additional Shared Facilities, to the extent such loss is not covered by the insurance required by Section 12. 3.9 Q506 Interconnection Agreement. The Co-Tenants agree that the Shared Assets include the Co-Tenants shared interests, rights and obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and that the Manager has been appointed to act as the representative of the Co-Tenants as the Interconnection Customer under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement in accordance with its terms and clause (d) of Exhibit I hereto. 3.10 Water Usage Pursuant to Shared Premises Agreements. 3.10.1 Future Shared Water Use Easement. Following the date hereof, the Co-Tenants will obtain certain water use easements (the Water Use Easement ) from SGS Antelope Valley Development, LLC, an affiliate of the Co-Tenants and the fee owner of their respective Project Sites. Such Water Use Easement shall be in a form mutually acceptable to all of the Co-Tenants and once executed, shall become a Shared Premises Agreement. 3.10.2 Water Usage - Operations. The Manager, on behalf of the Co-Tenants, shall install, repair, maintain, operate and relocate (as necessary) one or more water wells and related pipelines, pumps and related equipment (all of which shall constitute Shared Facilities) pursuant to the Water Use Easement prior to the commencement of operations of the first Project to achieve substantial completion. Each Co-Tenant shall be entitled to obtain and use water from such facilities for the purposes of cleaning of solar modules, landscaping and domestic use in connection with the operation of such Co-Tenant s Project and such water shall also be used for domestic water and sewer treatment purposes for the shared operations and maintenance building and related facilities; provided, however, that no Co-Tenant shall be entitled to use more than such Co-Tenant s Percentage Interest of the maximum volume of water that can be drawn from such well(s) (such maximum volume being set, from time to time, by the lesser of (i) the maximum volume allowed to be drawn under applicable federal, state or local law, regulation, court judgment or order that is applicable to the use of such wells, and (ii) the maximum sustained yield of such wells as determined by an independent consulting engineer, and shall be measured from February of such year to March of the following year). Further, each Co Tenant s withdrawal and use of such water shall be subject to any other requirements imposed by federal, state and local governmental authorities, water districts or other regulatory entities, including, without limitation, the Sustainable Ground Water Management Act. 3.10.3 Water Usage - Construction. During construction of each Co-Tenant s Project, such Co-Tenant shall have the right to obtain required water pursuant to the Water Supply Agreement for as long as such agreement remains in force and effect, and any Co-Tenant that obtains water for such purpose pursuant to the Water Supply Agreement shall have the sole obligation to pay for such water and to perform (or cause to be performed) any other obligations of the Purchaser under such Water Supply Agreement with respect to such water. The Manager, on behalf of the applicable Co-Tenants, shall administer the Water Supply Agreement during such construction activities, and at the request of any one or more Co-Tenants, shall seek to extend the term of such Water Supply Agreement, at no cost or expense to any non-requesting Co-Tenants. If the Water Supply Agreement expires or is terminated, each Co-Tenant shall be responsible to secure its own construction water supply. 4. SHARED EXPENSES AND CONSTRUCTION COSTS 4.1 Liabilities for the Account of the Co-Tenants; No Charging of Fees, Premiums or Profits. Except as specifically set forth in this Agreement, each Co-Tenant shall be solely responsible for its Liabilities relating to its Project and Project Specific Assets, including without limitation, all Liabilities arising from acquiring, designing, installing, constructing, using, operating, maintaining, repairing, replacing and removing its Project Specific Assets. Each Co-Tenant shall, at its sole cost and expense, maintain in good working order and repair at all times each part of its Project that connects with or which affects the Shared Facilities or the Shared Premises. Each Co-Tenant (or Co-Tenants, if any Additional Shared Assets are being acquired or installed at the joint expense of two or more Co-Tenants) acquiring or installing any Additional Shared Assets shall be responsible for, and pay, all Liabilities relating to the acquisition or installation, as applicable, of the Additional Shared Assets, except to the extent otherwise provided in Section 3.8. Further, each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for all Liabilities arising from such Co-Tenant s actions or inactions in violation of this Agreement, the Interconnection Agreements, the Shared Premises Agreements, Land Matters, Governmental Approvals and any other Shared Assets. The Co-Tenants agree that the purpose of this Agreement is for the Co-Tenants and their respective Projects to benefit from the cost savings, convenience and efficiencies that result from the sharing of the Shared Assets, and no Co-Tenant shall charge any other Co-Tenant any fee, premium or other profit relating to the Shared Assets or services provided under this Agreement. This Section 4.1 shall not be construed as prohibiting in any way any Co-Tenant s obligations to pay for the costs and expenses incurred in connection with the sharing, development, design, procurement, installation and/or construction of the Shared Assets or the provision of any services pursuant to this Agreement. 4.2 Shared Expenses. 4.2.1 The Co-Tenants each shall be responsible for and shall reimburse the Manager (in accordance with Section 4.3) for Liabilities arising under or relating to the following (collectively, the Shared Expenses ) and in the following described proportions: (a) for all those Co-Tenants which (i) have commenced construction of a Project or are operating a Project and (ii) are parties to a particular Shared Premises Agreement or an Interconnection Agreement and have rights to the portion of the Shared Premises or other Shared Assets provided therein, the Liabilities arising under such Shared Premises Agreement or such Interconnection Agreement and the use, maintenance, repair, and inspection of the applicable portion of such Shared Premises or Shared Assets, shall be shared by those Co-Tenants in proportion to their relative Percentage Interests (e.g., if two (2) Co-Tenants are parties to a Shared Premises Agreement, and each has an equal Percentage Interest, they shall share equally in the Shared Expense; if three Co-Tenants are parties to a Shared Premises Agreement, and they have Percentage Interests in the amounts of ten percent (10%), thirty percent (30%), and sixty percent (60%), they shall share in the Shared Expense in a ratio of 1:3:6, or expressed as fractions, 1/10 to 3/10 to 6/10); and (b) the Shared Facilities, in proportion to the Co-Tenants respective applicable Segment Interests therein, provided that a Co-Tenant shall not be responsible for Shared Expenses with respect to any Segment that it has not yet connected its Project to or otherwise begun the use of; provided that notwithstanding the foregoing clause (a) or (b), the costs described in Section 4.6 below, shall be shared in accordance with such Section. 4.2.2 Each Co-Tenant may, from time to time, propose additional categories or types of expenses to be Shared Expenses to be administered jointly by the Co-Tenants, or by the Manager at the direction of the Co-Tenants in accordance with this Section 4.2. Any such proposed expense must be approved by a Majority of the Co-Tenants, provided that any Co-Tenant that would not be subject to the payment of such expense and would not otherwise be affected by the incurrence of such expense shall no have no voting rights with respect to such new Shared Expenses and shall not be counted in calculating the required number of Co-Tenants to constitute a Majority of the Co-Tenants. 4.2.3 Notwithstanding the foregoing, none of the following shall constitute Shared Expenses: (a) the cost of developing and constructing the Shared Facilities, including without limitation, development, permitting, initial procurement, construction, installation, financing and any other costs incurred in connection with the Shared Facilities of any Project prior to sharing the use thereof in accordance with this Agreement (except as provided in Section 4.6); (b) the cost and expense of any Project Specific Assets (including without limitation, any liabilities arising out of or associated with Project Specific Assets) and the connection and integration of Project Specific Assets with any Shared Facilities (including without limitation, any design, procurement, construction, or installation costs); or (c) Liabilities under the Shared Premises Agreements which are also the subject of any other shared facilities or co-tenancy agreement among the Co-Tenants, and which liabilities and the responsibility thereof are addressed by such prior existing shared facilities agreement or co-tenancy agreement. 4.3 Invoicing, Late Payments. No later than ten (10) days after the end of each calendar month following the Effective Date, the Manager shall invoice the Co-Tenants for their respective portions of the Shared Expenses. Manager s invoice shall include a detailed breakdown of the Shared Expenses and each Co-Tenant s share of the Shared Expenses, along with wire transfer instructions for making payment to Manager. The Co-Tenants shall make all payments to Manager (or directly to the other Co-Tenants to whom the Shared Expenses may be payable) under this Section 4.3 by wire transfer of immediately available funds as provided in the Manager s invoice, within thirty (30) days of receipt of such invoice. All sums not paid within thirty (30) days after receipt of Manager s invoice shall thereafter bear interest at the Default Rate. Each Co-Tenant will have the right to audit, and receive supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant under this Agreement. If there is a dispute as to any amount invoiced by Manager, the Co-Tenants shall pay all amounts not in dispute in accordance with this Section 4.3. The Co-Tenants shall pay any disputed amount ultimately determined as payable with interest thereon at the Default Rate accruing from the date of receipt of the Manager s disputed invoice. 4.4 Construction Costs. Except as provided in Section 4.6 below: 4.4.1 Subject to any other funding arrangement entered into by any two or more Co-Tenants, each of the Co-Tenants shall fund the design, engineering, procurement, installation, construction, and permitting costs and expenses (including costs for required grading and building permits) required to complete the Segments it is responsible for constructing as set forth in Exhibit C attached hereto ( Construction Costs ). 4.4.2 To the extent more than one Co-Tenant is responsible for construction of a particular Segment pursuant to Exhibit C, those Co-Tenants shall be responsible for the Construction Costs in proportion to their applicable Segment Interests. If one or more Co-Tenants holding a Segment Interest require the use of the applicable Segment prior to any other Co-Tenants, the Co-Tenants requiring earlier use may elect in their discretion to construct the applicable Segment and enter into an arrangement with such Co-Tenants with respect to funding of the Construction Costs of that Segment. 4.4.3 The Co-Tenants so electing to construct a Segment shall provide written notice to the other Co-Tenants and Manager prior to commencing construction and within five (5) days of completing construction. The Co-Tenant responsible for constructing each Segment, as set forth in Exhibit C, or the Co-Tenant which elects to construct a Segment sooner as provided by this Section, shall be referred to herein as the Constructing Co-Tenant. 4.5 Reimbursement of Construction Costs. 4.5.1 Each Co-Tenant with a Segment Interest in any particular Segment, and any Co-Tenant which later obtains a Segment Interest in a particular Segment, shall reimburse the Constructing Co-Tenant(s) for that Segment in proportion to their relative Segment Interests, or as otherwise provided in Exhibit C, in each case (i) to the extent the Constructing Co-Tenant has funded such Co-Tenant s portion of the construction costs, and (ii) together with interest on such amounts accrued at the Interest Rate beginning on the date that such costs were incurred (the Applicable Construction Costs ). 4.5.2 Prior to connecting any Project Specific Assets to, or utilizing any portion of a Segment, a Co-Tenant which did not construct and did not previously fund its portion of the construction of the Segment ( Non-Constructing Co-Tenant ) shall provide written notice to the Constructing Co Tenant(s), the other Co-Tenants, and the Manager, of such Non-Constructing Co-Tenant s intent to use or connect to the Segment. Within fifteen (15) Business Days after receiving such notice, the Constructing Co-Tenant shall issue an invoice to the requesting Non-Constructing Co-Tenant for the Applicable Construction Costs. The Non-Constructing Co-Tenant shall pay the invoice for Applicable Construction Costs prior to commencing the use of such Segment or connecting a Project Specific Assets to such Segment. This Section is not intended to provide all Co Tenants with rights to use all Segments, but is only a mechanism for reimbursement of Applicable Construction Costs among Co-Tenants with Segment Interests as set forth on Exhibit C. A Co-Tenant with no Segment Interest in a particular Segment shall, except as provided in Section 6.16 below, be required to obtain the consent of all the Co-Tenants with Segment Interests in the applicable Segment prior to connecting any Project Specific Assets to, or utilizing such Segment, which consent may be denied in the Co-Tenants discretion, as all Segments are fully used by or fully allocated to a Project and shall be subject to all the terms and conditions of this Agreement, including Sections 3.5 and 3.6 above, and the obligation to reimburse the constructing Co-Tenants for any Applicable Construction Costs. 4.6 Q506 Interconnection Agreement Payments. 4.6.1 The Co-Tenants acknowledge that each Q506 Co-Tenant, other than the Constructing Co-Tenant, has provided a promissory note to fund its proportionate share of construction costs of the Shared Facilities set forth in Exhibit C, which includes all the interconnection facilities of the Interconnection Customer required to be constructed pursuant to the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, to the contractor constructing such facilities pursuant to that certain Engineering, Procurement and Construction Agreement, dated as of February 17, 2016, between the Phase 1 Project Company and SunPower Corporation, System. Each such Q506 Co-Tenant further agrees that the Phase 1 Project Company shall have no obligation to fund any such proportionate share of construction costs of such other Q506 Co-Tenants. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all costs to construct the portion of shared roads located within its applicable Project Site, with no obligation for any Co-Tenant to reimburse any other Co-Tenant therefor, except for the initial shared roads being constructed by the Phase 1 Project Company. 4.6.2 Notwithstanding if a Q506 Co-Tenant is the Construction Co-Tenant or not, the Q506 Co-Tenants each shall be responsible for and shall pay or cause to be paid, or reimburse the Manager (or shall cause the Manager to be reimbursed) in accordance with Section 4.3 for, all payments required to be made by the Interconnection Customer to the Participating TO under Section 13(a) of Appendix A to the Q506 Interconnection Agreement pro rata based on the Percentage Interest of each such Q506 Co-Tenants, as and when required under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. 5. USE OF SHARED ASSETS 5.1 Use by Projects. Subject to the other requirements of this Agreement and the Interconnection Agreements, each Co-Tenant shall have the rights to transmit and deliver electricity pursuant to the Interconnection Agreements in accordance with such Co-Tenant s Percentage Interest set forth in Exhibit D attached hereto. Subject to the other requirements of this Agreement, each Co-Tenant shall have the right to use each Segment of the Shared Facilities to the extent such Co-Tenant owns a Segment Interest in the applicable Segment, as set forth in Exhibit C attached hereto. Except as set forth in Section 5.2 below, the foregoing use rights include use of the capacity of any Segment used to collect, transmit, aggregate, transform, control, shape or otherwise regulate and/or carry electrical energy, including without limitation, any electrical transmission lines, transformers, substations, and other electrical components (collectively, Electrical Facilities ) in each Segment to collect and transmit electricity from and to the applicable Co-Tenant s Project only in an amount in proportion to such Co-Tenant s relative Segment Interest vis- -vis the other Co-Tenants with a Segment Interest in said Segment. 5.2 Use by Secondary Projects. Subject to Section 6.16 and the other requirements of this Agreement and the Interconnection Agreements, Secondary Project Co-Tenants shall have the right, and may assign such right to Third-Party Project Users, to use each Segment of the Shared Facilities in which they receive a Segment Interest in connection with their Secondary Projects. For the avoidance of any doubt, all the Co-Tenants acknowledge and agree that Secondary Project Co-Tenants may from time to time hold small or nominal Segment Interests, but they shall nonetheless be entitled to all the indicia of ownership of an interest in the Segment and they shall further be entitled to the following use rights. The use rights for Secondary Projects of Secondary Project Co-Tenants with respect to any Electrical Facilities need not be proportional to such Secondary Project Co-Tenant s relative Segment Interest in the Electrical Facilities vis- -vis the other Co-Tenants, and shall instead include a right to use all the capacity of any Electrical Facilities a Secondary Project Co-Tenant holds a Segment Interest in, subject only to the following limitations, conditions and covenants: 5.2.1 Secondary Project Co-Tenants shall, and shall cause their Third-Party Project Users to, curtail the energy output of their Secondary Projects to provide priority of use of Electrical Facilities to all other Co-Tenant s Projects and their respective energy outputs, in accordance with any procedures called for by the Interconnection Agreements, FERC and CAISO, as such procedures may be administered by the Manager and the manager under the Interconnection Agreements or any other agreement entered into by and among the applicable Co-Tenants. In the event of any conflict of use rights in Electrical Facilities between a Co Tenant s Project and any Secondary Project Co-Tenant s (or its Third-Party Project User s) Secondary Project, the Secondary Project Co-Tenant s and its Third-Party Project User s use rights in any Electrical Facilities shall be secondary and subordinate to the use rights of all other Co-Tenants Projects. OBLIGATIONS AND CERTAIN RIGHTS OF THE CO-TENANTS 6.1 Standards of Performance; Action, Omission or Failure to Perform an Obligation that Results in a Material Adverse Effect on Another Co-Tenant or that Co-Tenant s Project. No Co-Tenant will take any action, omit to take any action or fail to perform any obligation under this Agreement, the Shared Premises Agreements, the applicable Interconnection Agreements, Governmental Approvals, Land Matters, or Power Purchase Agreements, that materially and adversely affects any other Co-Tenant or another Co-Tenant s Project or gives rise to a Liability affecting any other Co-Tenant, another Co-Tenant s Project, or the Shared Assets, including any action, omission or failure to perform an obligation that results in damage to, disconnection of, or an outage of another Co-Tenant s Project. 6.2 Taxes. Unless otherwise directed by the Co-Tenants, the Manager shall pay all real and personal property Taxes, general or special, levied against the Shared Assets before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty will become due or be imposed for their non payment, except that the Manager may withhold payment of any Tax if Manager is contesting the payment of such Tax in good faith by appropriate proceedings and such proceeding does not involve any danger of the sale, forfeiture or loss of any part of such Shared Asset, including the posting of any bond that is required by applicable Law to avoid such sale, forfeiture or loss while the payment of such Tax is being contested and notifies all the Co-Tenants thereof in writing at least thirty (30) days before such payment is due or paid. The rights, duties, obligations and liabilities of the Co-Tenants under this Agreement will be individual and not joint or collective, and no Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the default of any other Co-Tenant under this Agreement. Each Co-Tenant operating a Project represents and warrants that, as of the date that such Project is energized, the Co-Tenant will be an EWG or its Project will be a QF, and each such Co-Tenant covenants to maintain its status as an EWG or its Project s status as a QF for so long as it is a party to this Agreement or has any interest in the Shared Assets that requires it to be an EWG or its Project to be a QF. To the extent any Governmental Authority attempts to compel the Co-Tenants to provide public access to or use of the Shared Assets, the Co-Tenants shall cooperate to dispute and resist such compulsion by any and all judicial, administrative, legislative, political and other legal means available, unless Majority of the Co-Tenants agree otherwise and no Co-Tenants Project is materially adversely affected thereby. Notwithstanding the foregoing, the Co-Tenants shall comply with any Governmental Approvals requirements. Additionally, to the extent any Co-Tenant Project s Governmental Approvals are expressly conditioned on providing a third party access to cross over the Shared Premises, such rights of access do not adversely impact the development, construction, operation, maintenance or repair of the Shared Facilities, any Project, or any part thereof, as confirmed by an Independent Engineer, and provided that no public right of access may be created in any Shared Facilities, all of which are the property of and allocated to the Co-Tenants and their Projects, the Co-Tenants shall cooperate in good faith and negotiate a resolution of such request to facilitate the Governmental Approvals. 6.10 Crossing and Co-Location Rights. Each Co-Tenant hereunder shall be permitted to cross and encroach upon the Shared Premises with its Project Specific Assets (including collection, communication and fiber lines, gas and water pipes, utility services, and access roads) solely to the extent necessary to develop, construct, operate and maintain its Project or a Secondary Project on its Project Site, provided that any such crossings, encroachments, or overhang shall be subject to the noninterference and overburdening protections of Section 3.5 above. In particular, any Co-Tenant s exercise of rights under this Section shall only be permitted in accordance with Prudent Industry Practices, and shall not interfere with or endanger the construction, operation, or maintenance of the Shared Facilities or other facilities already in place on the Shared Premises. Except as otherwise provided on Exhibit B-1 hereto, in the event of a conflict in the location or operation of the Shared Facilities and any Project Specific Assets on the Shared Premises, the Shared Facilities shall take priority over the Project Specific Assets, and any Project Specific Assets existing within the Shared Premises shall take priority over any subsequent Additional Shared Facilities or Project Specific Assets requiring the use of the Shared Premises. 6.11 Offtaker Collocation of Monitoring and Control Facilities with Shared Facilities. The Parties acknowledge and agree that their respective Offtakers may require the use of the Shared Premises for the collocation of certain control, metering, and monitoring equipment servicing the Projects. The Parties agree to cooperate in good faith to provide their respective Offtakers with rights to use the Shared Premises to so service the Projects. 6.12 Further Development Covenants. Co-Tenant to obtain and provide new (or amended existing) crossing agreements, subordination, and/or nondisturbance agreements relating to transmission, collection, facilities crossings and/or access The Co-Tenants shall do all of the following: (a) with the exception of information and data the Manager is required to record and collect hereunder, provide the Manager with all material information, including, but not limited to permits, agreements, data and documents for the Shared Assets that is reasonably required for Manager to perform its obligations under this Agreement or under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement; (b) examine all material documents submitted by Manager and render any necessary decisions pertaining thereto promptly; (c) promptly make material decisions required under this Agreement or any other agreement that the Manager may be requested to administer hereunder and respond to all reasonable requests from Manager for approval made hereunder; (d) promptly execute and deliver such evidence of Manager s authority hereunder as may be reasonably required by third parties; and (e) except where the same are being disputed in good faith, promptly make all payments and incur all expenditures required in connection with the Shared Assets in accordance with this Agreement, the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and the Shared Facilities O&M Budget. 6.15 Admission of New Co-Tenants. APN: 261-120-08-00-2 (PORTION) EXHIBIT I Q506 Interconnection Agreement Co-Tenancy Requirements Unless defined in Section 1.1 of this Agreement, capitalized terms used in this Exhibit I have the meanings given to them in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable for all obligations required of the Interconnection Customer set forth in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, including all affirmative covenants and all monetary obligations, the latter of which includes the financing of all Interconnection Facilities that are required to be financed by the Interconnection Customer in order to accommodate the interconnection of the entire Rosamond West Solar Project. (b) Except as expressly provided in this clause (b), there shall be no more than five (5) Co-Tenants comprising Interconnection Customer, and neither Interconnection Customer nor any Co-Tenant may further subdivide in any manner or form its interests in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. Notwithstanding the foregoing, Solar Star California XLI, LLC, Golden Fields Solar I, LLC, Golden Fields Solar II, LLC, Golden Fields Solar III, LLC, and Golden Fields Solar IV, LLC (or any successor permitted in accordance with Article 19 of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement,) may each assign a portion of its rights and obligations in the Interconnection Customer s Interconnection Facilities, and other rights and obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, to an Affiliate for the purpose of developing Phase 1 through Phase 5 of the Rosamond West Solar Project; provided that such assignment otherwise complies with all provisions of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement,, including this Exhibit I, and such Affiliate becomes a party to this Agreement and agrees to become a party to the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, and otherwise meets all of the requirements of a Co-Tenant under this Exhibit I. Upon any such assignment in accordance with Article 19 of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, and this Agreement, the Affiliate assignee shall be considered a Co-Tenant under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. The Interconnection Customer acknowledges that the administrative burden to the CAISO to administer the Q506 Interconnection Agreement would be excessive if the Interconnection Customer or a Co-Tenant were to further subdivide its interests in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement in violation of this clause (b) and any such action would be considered a Breach and Default under Article 17 of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, entitling the CAISO to terminate the Q506 Interconnection Agreement in accordance with such Article 17. The Co-Tenants acknowledge that Interconnection Customer and each Co-Tenant may assign its rights in the Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities and the Q506 Interconnection Agreement for collateral security purposes in accordance with Article 19 of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. (c) No Co-Tenant may assign its interests as tenant-in-common in the Interconnection Customer s Interconnection Facilities, and other rights and obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, independently of its interest in the Rosamond West Solar Project. Subject to the foregoing, and subject to the limitation in clause (b) above, the Co-Tenants acknowledge that Interconnection Customer and each Co-Tenant may assign its rights in the Interconnection Customer s Interconnection Facilities and its rights and obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement in accordance with Article 19 of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, including for collateral security purposes, provided that such assignment does not result in an increase in the number of Co-Tenants. (d) In accordance with the terms of this Agreement, the Co-Tenants shall appoint the Manager, who shall have no interest as the Interconnection Customer but shall serve as the Interconnection Customer s authorized agent and representative for purposes of administering the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. The Manager will be a single point of contact for CAISO and Participating TO and will represent Interconnection Customer for notice purposes and all other communications between and among CAISO, Participating TO, and Interconnection Customer. All payments, insurance, and security to be provided by the Interconnection Customer to the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to the Q506 Interconnection Agreement shall be provided only by the Manager on behalf of all Co-Tenants, and any invoices or refunds due to the Interconnection Customer by the Participating TO shall be made only to the Manager on behalf of all Co-Tenants. Manager shall bear all responsibility for disseminating notices, communications, and all interactions among the Co-Tenants, and each Co-Tenant hereby waives any right to individual notice or communication from CAISO or Participating TO. The CAISO and the Participating TO will not be obligated to act on any instructions from a Co-Tenant. The Manager s actions and representations to CAISO and Participating TO shall be binding upon the Interconnection Customer and each individual Co-Tenant. Interconnection Customer and each individual Co-Tenant shall be jointly and severally liable and responsible for the Manager s actions. The Manager shall have the power to exercise and shall exercise any and all of the rights of the Manager under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and shall coordinate compliance with the Q506 Interconnection Agreement by the Co-Tenants; provided that the Manager may not terminate, amend or transfer the Q506 Interconnection Agreement or waive any material rights of the Co-Tenants under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, without the prior, unanimous written consent of the Co-Tenants. (e) The Co-Tenants agree that, for the purposes of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement, the entire 304.705 MW (gross) comprising the Rosamond West Solar Project shall be considered to be a single Generating Facility. No Co-Tenant shall have any expectation that the CAISO will treat any portion of the Rosamond West Solar Project as a stand-alone Generating Facility or differently from any other portion of the Generating Facility. Co-Tenants shall act as a single entity in undertaking the obligations of Interconnection Customer under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement. CAISO and Participating TO shall treat all Co-Tenants comprising the Interconnection Customer as a single entity under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and bear no obligation or responsibility to any individual Co-Tenant. Performance of the Interconnection Customer s obligations under the Q506 Interconnection Agreement shall not be excused by reason of any Co-Tenant s failure to agree with respect to any obligation of the Interconnection Customer thereunder. (f) In the event of a conflict between the terms of the Q506 Interconnection Agreement and the terms of this Agreement, the terms of Q506 Interconnection Agreement shall govern. (g) The Q506 Interconnection Agreement shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of electricity generated by or on behalf of a Project owned by a Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors, assigns or affiliates) as set forth in the Q506 Interconnection Agreement.

Availability: Golden Fields Solar I, LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy, capacity, and ancillary services available under this Market-Based Rate Tariff ("Tariff") to any purchaser with whom Seller has contracted, except as prohibited below. 2. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 3. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller. 4. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 1 seller in all regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a). 5. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff. 6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received: (1) waiver of Subparts B and C of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; (2) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees is not granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and 141 (with the exception of sections 141.14 and 141.15); and (3) blanket authorization under Section 204 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824c, and 18 C.F.R. Part 34 for all future issuances of securities and assumptions of liabilities. Golden Fields Solar I, LLC, Docket No. ER16-2289-000 (2016). 7. Ancillary Services: Seller also will make available to any purchaser with whom it has contracted the following ancillary services: a. PJM: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection. b. New York: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc. c. New England: Seller offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc. d. California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO. e. MISO: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. (MISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. f. Southwest Power Pool: Seller offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. (SPP) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. g. Ancillary Services - Third-Party Provider: Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, Operating Reserve-Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 8. Revisions to Tariff: Seller may file revisions to this Tariff with the Commission. Nothing contained in this Tariff shall be construed as affecting or limiting in any way the right of Seller to unilaterally file with the Commission for a change in any aspect of this Tariff under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act, 16 U.S.C. 824d, and the Commission's rules and regulations promulgated thereunder. 9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective as of the date specified by the Commission. - 2 -
